We solve the equation for y in terms of x.
            \begin{align*}
                -3y \amp =6 - 4x\\
                y \amp = \frac{6 - 4x}{-3}
                =\frac{6}{-3}+\frac{-4x}{-3}\\
                y \amp = -2+\frac{4}{3}x
            \end{align*}

We see that the slope of the line is m = \dfrac{4}{3} and its vertical intercept is b = -2. We begin by plotting the y-intercept, (0, -2). We then use the slope to find another point on the line. We have
        m = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x}=\frac{4}{3}
        so starting at (0, -2), we move 4 units in the y-direction and 3 units in the x-direction, to arrive at the point (3, 2). Finally, we draw the line through these two points. (See .)
